    {"parentUuid":"0e542947-24e0-4070-88e8-f90312338df3","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"abb8ef584f1a56500","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01EU5CuVYK8f7vekgAf5ZDTj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The analysis document has been written to `/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/literature/primecount_analysis.md`.\n\n**Summary of findings:**\n\n**Algorithm:** Primecount uses Gourdon's (2001) variant of Deleglise-Rivat, decomposing pi(x) into components A + B + C + D + Phi0 + Sigma with two independent alpha parameters (alpha_y, alpha_z). Complexity is O(x^{2/3} / log^2 x), a log^2 x improvement over bare O(x^{2/3}).\n\n**The 100-1000x speedup over naive Lucy DP comes from:**\n1. **Asymptotic improvement:** O(x^{3/4}) vs O(x^{2/3}/log^2 x) -- a factor of ~10^5 at x=10^22\n2. **POPCNT counter array** replacing Fenwick tree (5-10x from cache efficiency)\n3. **SIMD kernels** (AVX512/ARM SVE) in inner loops (4-8x)\n4. **libdivide** replacing integer division with multiply+shift (1.4x for easy leaves)\n5. **Segmented L1-cached PiTable** and mod-240 wheel sieve (2-4x each)\n6. **OpenMP parallelism** with adaptive load balancer scaling to 100+ cores (20-30x on 32 cores)\n7. **32-bit arithmetic** fast paths where values fit (2-3x for division-heavy code)\n\n**Key parallelization insight:** Gourdon's 2002 modification splits hard special leaves into independent chunks, enabling embarrassingly parallel execution without thread synchronization.\n\n**Bottom line for our project:** Even with all these optimizations, primecount needs ~10^62 operations for p(10^100). The engineering is maxed out; only a fundamentally new algorithm can reach our target."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5662,"cache_read_input_tokens":38503,"output_tokens":461,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation